Mr Sato, 56, said he saw 10 to 15 men walking towards them who he assumed were members of the Free Syrian Army, who had been accompanying them.

He told CBS news: 'I held up my camera and started shooting. It was then that it happened.

'I thought I was going to be hit and that's when I was separated from Mika. At no point did I think that she had died.

'I asked a rebel fighter where Mika was. He told me, "She's at the hospital, go and see for yourself." 'At that point I pretty much imagined what had happened to her.

